SIMPLE: sharp
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sharp
<hw>Sharp</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Sharper</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Sharpest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sharp</ets>,
<ets>scharp</ets>, <ets>scarp</ets>, AS. <ets>scearp</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>skarp</ets>, LG. <ets>scharp</ets>, D. <ets>scherp</ets>, G.
<ets>scharf</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>skarp</ets>, Icel. <ets>skarpr</ets>.
Cf. <er>Escarp</er>, <er>Scrape</er>, <er>Scorpion</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Having a very thin edge or fine point; of a nature to
cut or pierce easily; not blunt or dull; keen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He dies upon my scimeter's <qex>sharp</qex> point.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Terminating in a point or edge; not obtuse or
rounded; somewhat pointed or edged; peaked or ridged; <as>as, a
<ex>sharp</ex> hill; <ex>sharp</ex> features.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Affecting the sense as if pointed or cutting, keen,
penetrating, acute: to the taste or smell, pungent, acid, sour, as
ammonia has a <xex>sharp</xex> taste and odor; to the hearing, piercing,
shrill, as a <xex>sharp</xex> sound or voice; to the eye,
instantaneously brilliant, dazzling, as a <xex>sharp</xex>
flash.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>High in pitch; acute;
<as>as, a <ex>sharp</ex> note or tone</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>Raised a semitone in pitch; <as>as, C <ex>sharp</ex> (C⟦sharp⟧),
which is a half step, or semitone, higher than C</as>.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>So high as to be out of tune, or above true pitch;
<as>as, the tone is <ex>sharp</ex>; that instrument is
<ex>sharp</ex></as>. Opposed in all these senses to
<ant>flat</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Very trying to the feelings; piercing; keen; severe;
painful; distressing; <as>as, <ex>sharp</ex> pain, weather; a
<ex>sharp</ex> and frosty air</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sharp</qex> misery had worn him to the bones.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The morning <qex>sharp</qex> and clear.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In <qex>sharpest</qex> perils faithful proved.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Cutting in language or import; biting; sarcastic;
cruel; harsh; rigorous; severe; <as>as, a <ex>sharp</ex>
rebuke</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧That <xex>sharp</xex> look.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To that place the <qex>sharp</qex> Athenian law⟦br⟧
Can not pursue us.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be thy words severe,⟦br⟧
<qex>Sharp</qex> as merits but the sword forbear.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Of keen perception; quick to discern or distinguish;
having nice discrimination; acute; penetrating; sagacious; clever;
<as>as, a <ex>sharp</ex> eye; <ex>sharp</ex> sight, hearing, or
judgment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing makes men <qex>sharper</qex> . . . than want.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many other things belong to the material world, wherein the
<qex>sharpest</qex> philosophers have never ye<?/ arrived at clear and
distinct ideas.</q> <rj><qau>L. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Eager in pursuit; keen in quest; impatient for
gratification; keen; <as>as, a <ex>sharp</ex> appetite</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Fierce; ardent; fiery; violent; impetuous.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧In <xex>sharp</xex> contest of battle.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>sharp</qex> assault already is begun.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Keenly or unduly attentive to one's own interest;
close and exact in dealing; shrewd; <as>as, a <ex>sharp</ex> dealer; a
<ex>sharp</ex> customer.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The necessity of being so <qex>sharp</qex> and exacting.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>Composed of hard, angular grains; gritty; <as>as,
<ex>sharp</ex> sand</as>.</def> <rj><au>Moxon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>Steep; precipitous; abrupt; <as>as, a
<ex>sharp</ex> ascent or descent; a <ex>sharp</ex> turn or
curve</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <fld>(Phonetics)</fld> <def>Uttered in a whisper, or
with the breath alone, without voice, as certain consonants, such as
<xex>p</xex>, <xex>k</xex>, <xex>t</xex>, <xex>f</xex>; surd; nonvocal;
aspirated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Sharp</xex> is often used in the formation of
self-explaining compounds; as, <xex>sharp</xex>-cornered,
<xex>sharp</xex>-edged, <xex>sharp</xex>-pointed,
<xex>sharp</xex>-tasted, <xex>sharp</xex>-visaged, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sharp practice</b></col>, <cd>the getting of an
advantage, or the attempt to do so, by a tricky expedient.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>To brace sharp</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To sharp
up</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to turn the yards to the
most oblique position possible, that the ship may lie well up to the
wind.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Keen; acute; piercing; penetrating; quick;
sagacious; discerning; shrewd; witty; ingenious; sour; acid; tart;
pungent; acrid; severe; poignant; biting; acrimonious; sarcastic;
cutting; bitter; painful; afflictive; violent; harsh; fierce; ardent;
fiery.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sharp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sharp
<hw>Sharp</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To a point
or edge; piercingly; eagerly; sharply.</def> <rj><au>M.
Arnold.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The head [of a spear] full <qex>sharp</qex> yground.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You bite so <qex>sharp</qex> at reasons.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Precisely; exactly; <as>as, we shall start at ten
o'clock <ex>sharp</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Look sharp</b></col>, <cd>attend; be alert.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sharp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sharp
<hw>Sharp</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sharp tool or
weapon.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If butchers had but the manners to go to <qex>sharps</qex>,
gentlemen would be contented with a rubber at cuffs.</q>
<rj><qau>Collier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The character
[⟦sharp⟧] used to indicate that the note before which it is placed is to
be raised a half step, or semitone, in pitch.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A
sharp tone or note.</def> <au>Shak.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A portion of a stream where the water runs very
rapidly.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>C.
Kingsley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A sewing needle having a very slender point; a
needle of the most pointed of the three grades, <xex>blunts</xex>,
<xex>betweens</xex>, and <xex>sharps</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Same as <er>Middlings</er>,
1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An expert.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sharp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sharp
<hw>Sharp</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sharped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sharping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sharpen.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To raise above the proper pitch;
to elevate the tone of; especially, to raise a half step, or semitone,
above the natural tone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sharp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Sharp
<hw>Sharp</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To play tricks in
bargaining; to act the sharper.</def> <rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To sing above the proper
pitch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sharp-cut</ent>⟦br⟧
